Endocytic condensate theory project

recent progress

  • long simulations are running well with all forces turned on

Endocytic condensate experimental project

purified protein approach

  • see Nikhil's protein purification project

in vivo approach

  • trial experiments on different microscopes indicate our airyscan should work well for 3D quantitative characterization of condensates over time
    • typically 5-10 s per ~ 30μm X 30μm X 10 μm volume, single channel
    • minimal photobleaching even after ~10 minutes continuous imaging

  • example 3D max projection

    • I was initially worried about splitting events being caused by actin polymerization, but Tyler pointed out this is actually pretty exciting since it makes fusion events much more common and therefore more measurable; no other condensate system common in the literature has this feature
  • LatA-treated cells do not passively split and fuse condensates, but they will likely be useful for FRAP experiments since the cytoplasm is much less active
  • designed approach for estimating condensate viscosity and surface tension from integrated analysis of FRAP and condensate fusion data; planning to begin experiments with Vinu at the end of the week

    • viscosity and surface tension of condensates can be estimated via Stokes-Einstein relation if diffusion coefficient and fusion-relaxation timescale can be measured (assuming Newtonian fluid)

      \(\tau / l = \frac{\eta}{\gamma}\) (\(\tau\) = fusion relaxation timescale, \(l\) = average droplet diameter, \(\eta\) = viscosity of the medium, \(\gamma\) = surface tension, \(\frac{\eta}{\gamma}\) = inverse capillary velocity)

      \(D = k_B T/6 \pi \eta R_h\) (\(D\) = diffusion coefficient, \(k_B\) = Boltzmann constant, \(\eta\) = viscosity of the medium, \(R_h\) = hydrodynamic radius of the probe molecule)

Vinu's modeling project

project overview

  1. modify my original simple model of CME with a condensate to make a constant coated membrane curvature instead of constant area
  2. perform similar analyses as I have already done to determine what the contribution from the condensate is:
    • when is it assistive to internalization?
    • when does it stall internalization?
  3. determine sensitivity of contribution to relevant parameters
    • volume of condensate
    • interfacial tensions of condensate
    • membrane tension
    • polymerization energy of clathrin coat
    • turgor pressure
  4. if time allows, characterize material properties of in vivo ede1 cytoplasmic condensates in order to constrain model parameters
    • contact angle with membrane can inform about relative surface tensions
    • FRAP speed can inform about viscosity
    • timescale of merging/splitting events can inform about relative surface tension/viscosity

updates

  • Vinu finished building the constant-curvature alternative model

  • it is indeed able to produce the same qualitative effect of a free energy barrier as my original model (don't pay attention to the y-axis scale in these plots; it's arbitrary)
    • my constant coat area model:

    • Vinu's constant curvature model:

  • however, the models are different because the condensate does not affect the slope of the free energy at h=0 in Vinu's model, whereas mine is always a positive slope

    • my constant area model contains condensate terms:

    • Vinu's constant curvature model does not contain condensate terms:

  • we are currently looking into the second derivative of Vinu's model to see whether there are still any general rules about the energy barrier at low h
  • we are also constructing a hybrid model where both the coat area and curvature are able to change. this can be analyzed as a free energy landscape on top of a contour plot such as this to show possible trajectories from flat to fully formed vesicle:
